# Working conventions for this workspace — {DOMAIN} OS

You operate the {DOMAIN} OS. Your job is not just to file things — it is to keep the system **current,
compounding, and self-describing**, and to decide "done" and "consistent" by evidence (a
`{OS}-system-check-health` run), not by feeling. Act autonomously on the rules below. (AGENTS.md is a
symlink to this file, so editing this file updates both.)

## The two modes of work — always know which you're in
- **One-off / output work** — a deliverable or answer that won't repeat. It goes in
  `work/{project}/YYYY-MM-DD-…/` and never earns a top-level folder.
- **System / design work** — improving the OS itself: a new skill, template, doctor check, routing
  rule, folder, or `CLAUDE.md` edit. This compounds; spend ~half your effort here (50/50).

Name which mode a task is, then act accordingly. Confusing the two is how workspaces rot.

## Auto-manage loop (run on new input, without being asked)
1. Place the raw file in its correct home, dated YYYY-MM-DD (create the folder if it doesn't exist yet).
2. Read it.
3. Extract reusable value into `knowledge/` (insights / faqs / decisions) — create `knowledge/` if absent.
4. Scan the related {ENTITY}/{PIPELINE} folder; read its README; reconcile.
5. Update everything affected in the SAME turn: entity READMEs, `{PIPELINE}/_board.md`,
   `artifacts/dashboard.html`, metrics. (never-stale rule)
6. Move folders to match reality (stage changes); update the external system of record if any.
7. Mine for compounding assets (templates, proof, FAQs).
8. Append a line to `PROGRESS.md`, then report what changed.

Confirm before inventing {DOMAIN} facts; otherwise just do the routine filing and summarize.

## Grow the structure on demand (don't pre-build; don't hoard folders)
The workspace starts as a lean spine (`plugin/ routines/ scripts/ docs/ work/` + root files). Create a
top-level folder the moment real material needs it — `knowledge/`, a pipeline, an entity folder, or a
brand-new one-word folder the domain genuinely calls for — and never create folders speculatively.
Every top-level folder and file name is a single lowercase word. When you add or rename a folder you
own the consequence: update this file's filing tree in the same turn.

## Self-updating brain (you MUST keep this file current)
This file is the brain; a stale brain is the worst drift there is. Whenever the system changes — a new
folder, a new skill, a new convention, a new routine, a moved boundary — update `CLAUDE.md` in the SAME
turn so it always matches reality. `AGENTS.md` is a symlink, so it follows automatically. The doctor
checks brain currency; don't make it catch a lie.

## Always append to PROGRESS.md
Every work session, append one entry to the root `PROGRESS.md` — no exceptions:

```
## YYYY-MM-DD
- **{what you did}** — {why it was done, 1-2 sentences}.
```

Pitch it between technical and plain-English so a human and an agent both understand it. It's a log:
date, thing done, why. Append; never rewrite history.

## Never stale (checked, not felt)
If you touched the project, leave it consistent — "consistent" is what `{OS}-system-check-health`
reports, not a feeling. After any change, ask which other files now disagree with reality and update
them all. `{OS}-system-fix-drift` (the janitor) runs the doctor + fixes drift on a schedule (its
runnable prompt is `routines/janitor.md`).

## Compound learning + self-improvement (get smarter every session)
Deposit at least one durable learning each session (a decision, faq, insight, or an improved
template/skill). Search `knowledge/` before solving anything — never twice. Improve the **system**, not
only its contents: when the same friction recurs, run `{OS}-system-improve-machinery` (reflect) to turn
it into a new skill, routing row, doctor check, or rule, logged to `operations/improvements.md`.

## After work, ask: "skillify this?"
When you finish a task, ask whether it will repeat, need upkeep, or prevent a failure from recurring.
If yes, run `{OS}-system-promote-skill` (skillify): it stages a draft in `work/`, verifies it, then
(with approval) publishes it and repackages. **Every skill lives in `plugin/skills/` — never author one
outside this workspace or outside that folder** — and is named `{OS}-{area}-{verb}-{noun}` (4 words;
maintenance organs use the area `system`). Reusable scripts go in `scripts/`.

## Agent compatibility
`plugin/skills/` is the source of truth. `.agents/skills` points there so Cursor and Codex discover the
same skills. Don't edit `.agents/skills` directly, and don't create `.cursor/skills` unless asked.

## Filing decision tree
1. Reusable instrument (template/checklist/boilerplate)? -> `library/`
2. Reusable executable script? -> `scripts/`
3. A task that will repeat or need upkeep? -> run `{OS}-system-promote-skill` (skill lands in `plugin/skills/`)
4. A finalized output you regenerate (dashboard, recurring report)? -> `artifacts/`
5. A one-off / ad-hoc build (won't repeat)? -> `work/{project}/YYYY-MM-DD-…/`
6. Reusable answer/insight/decision/SOP? -> `knowledge/`
7. Human-facing doc about how this OS works? -> `docs/`
8. Flowing item not yet done? -> `{PIPELINE}/`
9. Tied to a core entity? -> `{ENTITY}/`
10. A workflow to run on a schedule / unattended? -> a routine prompt in `routines/` (indexed in `routines/README.md`)
11. Something genuinely new the domain needs? -> a new one-word top-level folder — then update this tree.

## Don't
- Don't leave the system stale, the brain outdated, or `PROGRESS.md` un-appended after a session.
- Don't invent facts the user must own — mark inferred items "draft — confirm".
- Don't pre-create empty folders; don't author a skill outside `plugin/skills/`.
